<P> This may seem like quite a job, but if you build this as a series
of functions, you'll find it's straightforward.  We will start by giving
you the following two functions:

<BLOCKQUOTE> <PRE>
void drawLine(int length)
{
  int i;

  for (i = 0; i &lt;&#32; length; i++)
    printf("x");
  printf("\n");
}

void drawBlanks(int n)
{
  int i;

  for (i = 0; i &lt;&#32; n; i++)
    printf(" ");
}
</PRE> </BLOCKQUOTE>

<P> <TT>drawLine</TT> takes a number of <TT>x</TT>'s to write and
writes them, followed by a newline.  <TT>drawBlanks</TT> is similar,
except its parameter is a number of spaces to write and it doesn't
write a newline.  With <TT>drawLine</TT> we can write
pieces of most of the numbers, like the top and bottom of the 0,
the top, middle, and bottom of the 2, 3, 5, 6, 8, and 9.

<P> So consider writing the 0.  You also need to write a variety
of lines where each line contains an <TT>x</TT>, a number of blanks,
and another <TT>x</TT>.  Write a function, <TT>drawEndPoints</TT>,
that takes the length of a line and the number of lines you want
to write, and uses them to write these lines.  For example,
<TT>drawEndPoints(5, 3)</TT> should produce the following output:
<BLOCKQUOTE><PRE>
x   x
x   x
x   x
</PRE> </BLOCKQUOTE>
Hint: To write it, think about how you could use <TT>drawBlanks</TT>
to write the blanks in each line.

<P> Now consider the 1 (and, in fact, the 7).  It's similar to the 0,
but to write it, we need to write spaces before the <TT>x</TT> on each
line.   So write
a function, <TT>drawRightEndPoints</TT>, that takes the same
parameters as <TT>drawEndPoints</TT>, except that it writes lines
like those we need for the 1.  For example,
<TT>drawRightEndPoints(5, 3)</TT> should produce this output:
<BLOCKQUOTE><PRE>
    x
    x
    x
</PRE> </BLOCKQUOTE>

<P> Given these functions, you can now easily write the
functions <TT>drawZero</TT>, <TT>drawOne</TT>, and <TT>drawSeven</TT>
to take care of 3 of the 10 digits we need to write.  Do so and
test them and you are done with this part.  Name the source file
holding all of this information <B>numbers1.c</B>.

<P><B><A NAME=part4>Part 4</A></B>: Copy the program from the
previous part of the assignment into a file named <B>numbers2.c</B>.  Now
you'll need to finish the last set of numbers.  Without writing any
new functions, you can write the functions, <TT>drawThree</TT>, 
<TT>drawFour</TT>, <TT>drawEight</TT>, and <TT>drawNine</TT> to write
the 3, 4, 8, and 9 respectively.  (The trick here is figuring
how to calculate the correct value to pass to your
<TT>drawEndPoints</TT> and <TT>drawRightEndPoints</TT> functions.)

<P> To handle the remaining values, you need to write a function
that we can use to write the top part of the 5, and the 
bottom part of the 2 and 6.   This function, <TT>drawLeftEndPoints</TT>,
takes the same arguments as its companion drawing functions, and
produces a series of lines containing only a single "x" at the start of
each line.
For example, <TT>drawLeftEndPoints(5, 3)</TT> should produce this output:
<BLOCKQUOTE><PRE>
x
x
x
</PRE> </BLOCKQUOTE>
(Actually, this function doesn't need to take the length of the line,
but to make it look just like the other functions, we might as well
write it to take the same parameters.)  Given this you can write
the last three functions: <TT>drawTwo</TT>, <TT>drawFive</TT>,
and <TT>drawSix</TT>.

<P> Now you have one final task.  Write the final version of
the main program that can read the desired height and width to use
for all the numbers and then calls the number drawing functions in
order.  To make things simple, you can assume that the user will
always enter an <EM>odd</EM> number for the height.

